I remember the day we left the hospital together, it was snowing just like today. 19 year old me, with all 4 pounds 7 ounces of you. I sat in the back with my arms wrapped tight around your car seat, and I prayed for strength. I wanted to protect you from EVERYTHING. Turns out I couldn’t, and as hard as I tried I didn’t. Because it’s not possible…we are just human and life is just life. Sometimes it’s beautiful, and sometimes it’s more than we think we can bare. But it’s all of that that makes us who we are…AND I LOVE WHO YOU ARE. Happy 23rd Birthday my sweet boy. 02/23/23 🫶🏼

Dear Dad, 
It’s been such a long cold winter. I had to stop thinking about you for a little while because it hurt too much. So I traded pain for emptiness. I don’t know what’s worse. I guess emptiness, pain at least reminds me I’m still alive. But what is life without you? Cold. I used to like the cold but now that you’re gone it’s more than I can handle and I need the warmth of the sun. You’d be 73 today. You should be 73 today. But this life isn’t promised and the world isn’t fair. You taught me that. You taught me everything you knew, except how to live without you…or maybe that was laced through every word. And maybe I’m forgetting the most important lesson. And maybe the sun came out today just for a minute just to remind me that you’re still here. So maybe I don’t have to pick between pain and emptiness. Maybe there is another option I just can’t see because these tears are making my vision so foggy. It’s snowing now so maybe I’ll sit by the fireplace. Was that the lesson Dad? That we have to create our own warmth? Or that the warmth of the sun is always there even if we can’t see it through the fog? Am I getting warmer? I’m so sorry I forgot. Could you teach me one more thing Dad? How to be more like you. 

Love, rachel
